  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me in Naples. Growing up with parents who had different educational backgrounds—one with only primary school and the other with a bachelor's degree—teaches me that expectations can shape reality. When I was younger, my dad, who worked in construction, would say, 'You're smart, but not all boys are meant for engineering.' That kind of subtle pressure, even from someone close, can make a huge difference. Stereotype threat is when people feel anxious about confirming a negative stereotype about their group, like girls being bad at math or Black students failing in science. It's not just about being 'less capable'; it's about the fear of being judged or failing in a way that reinforces existing biases. I've seen this in my community—students who avoid STEM because they think they're 'not the right type.' Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big, top-down solutions that ignore the real-world context. In Naples, where many families are struggling with limited resources, we need practical, community-based approaches. For example, local schools could partner with businesses like my own sales job to show students that STEM isn't just for the elite—it's practical, relevant, and can lead to jobs in construction, logistics, or even small business management. We should also focus on creating safe spaces where students feel supported, not criticized. My own high neuroticism and tendency to overthink mean I know how easy it is to spiral when you're already stressed. That's why addressing stereotype threat needs to be done gently, with empathy and understanding. It's not about fixing people—it's about changing the environment so they don't have to worry about fitting into a box that doesn't exist for them.",
